# NestJS + Prisma Standards for this project

## File Structure

- Use feature-based modular structure (`auth/`, `tasks/`, `common/`)
- DTOs inside `dto/` folder
- Guards and Strategies in specific subfolders
- Services must be injectable and loosely coupled

## Code Conventions

### Naming
- **Classes**: PascalCase (`TasksService`, `CreateTaskDto`)
- **Methods**: camelCase (`findAll`, `createTask`)
- **Variables**: camelCase
- **Interfaces/Types**: PascalCase with `I` prefix only when necessary

### Prisma
- Always use explicit `select` to avoid leaking sensitive data
- Use `include` only when necessary
- Handle `NotFoundException` in Services
- Never expose `password` in responses

### Redis Caching
- Key prefix: `tasks:user:{userId}:*`
- TTL configurable via `REDIS_TTL`
- Invalidate cache on all write operations (`create`, `update`, `delete`)

### Error Handling
- Use global `AllExceptionsFilter`
- Throw specific `HttpException` (`NotFoundException`, `ConflictException`, `UnauthorizedException`)
- Never use `console.error` in production (use NestJS Logger)

### Security
- All Tasks endpoints must use `JwtAuthGuard`
- Extract `userId` from `req.user.userId`
- Never return passwords or sensitive data

### AI Service
- Keep `categorizeTask(description: string)` method async
- Ready to be replaced with real LLM integration

## SOLID Best Practices

- **S**: Each class has a single responsibility
- **O**: Open for extension (e.g. new AI provider)
- **L**: Liskov substitution respected
- **I**: Small and specific interfaces
- **D**: Depend on abstractions (PrismaService injected)

## Validation

- Use `class-validator` in all DTOs
- Global `@UsePipes(ValidationPipe)` in `main.ts`
- `whitelist: true` + `forbidNonWhitelisted: true`

This rule applies to **all** `.ts` files in the project.
